## What to produce

{{ pages | length }} files, one per page, with the exact filenames:

{%- for p in pages %}

  `intake/{{ slug }}/{{ "%02d" | format(p.number) }}.transcript.md`
{%- endfor %}

**Write each transcript file IMMEDIATELY after producing it**, in
the listed order (lowest page number first). This is important
because Codex calls can be interrupted — partial progress on disk
is more useful than losing all transcripts to a single interruption
near the end.

**Special case for `01.jpg`**: this is the COVER PAGE. It is not a
question page — it is the AQA/Edexcel/OCR exam cover with the
candidate name boxes, the marking grid, the exam title, the time
allowed, and the total marks. The expected output for this file
is a brief description of what the cover page shows, not a
transcript of handwritten answers (there should be no handwriting
on the cover, or only the candidate name if the student wrote it).
Keep this transcript file SHORT — page identification + a one-paragraph
description of the cover's contents + the verdict line. Do not
invent handwriting that isn't there.

For the other pages, each transcript file must contain three
sections, in this order:

### 1. Page identification (4-6 lines)

Read the printed exam page first. Report:
- The paper code printed at the bottom of the page
- The page number printed at the top of the page
- The question numbers visible on the page
- The total marks available on the page
- One sentence describing the printed context (the question wording,
  any apparatus table, any diagram referenced). Do not transcribe
  the printed question word-for-word — a short summary is fine.

### 2. Verbatim transcript of the student's handwritten answers

For each answer space on the page, in order, transcribe the
handwriting **verbatim** — every word, every crossed-out word, every
margin scribble, every arithmetic step, every annotation, every
diagram. Conventions:
- Wrap each answer in a `### Q... (N marks)` header.
- For text: write the literal words, including spelling mistakes,
  grammar mistakes, and missing punctuation. Do NOT correct to
  proper English.
- For chemistry symbols, equations, formulas, or working: write
  them in inline code with backticks, using plain-text
  approximations (e.g. `NH4Cl`, `2Na + Cl2 -> 2NaCl`,
  `proton number: 12`, `nucleon number: 24`). Preserve the line
  breaks of the working.
- For numbers and arithmetic: write them exactly as written, even
  if the arithmetic is wrong.
- For ticked MCQ options: write `Ticked: <letter>`. If multiple
  options are ticked or ambiguous, note the uncertainty.
- For diagrams or drawings (e.g. particle diagrams, electronic
  configurations, dot-and-cross diagrams, graphs with plotted
  points and drawn lines): describe in one or two short sentences
  in brackets. Do not attempt to interpret diagrams as text. For
  graphs: report the number of plotted points (count carefully),
  their approximate coordinates, the equation and shape of any
  drawn line(s), and the coordinates of any intersection. The
  marking pass needs enough detail to award markscheme points for
  best-fit lines, plotted crosses, and read-off values.
- For ticked statements in a list: write `Ticked: <statement>`.
- For illegible words or numbers: write `[illegible]` and note the
  position. Do not guess.
- For empty answer spaces: write `(no answer written)`.
- For crossed-out words: write the original word followed by
  `(crossed out)`.
- For scribbles / doodles in margins: ignore.

**CRITICAL — DO NOT REWRITE OR CORRECT THE STUDENT'S WORK.** This
applies to prose, arithmetic, and chemistry. The marking pass is a
separate step that compares the transcript to the markscheme; we
need the transcript to be a faithful record of the page, not a
sanitised version.

After the verbatim transcript, add one short sentence in italics
starting `*Reading note:*` describing your confidence. Be specific
about which words or numbers you are sure of and which you are not.
For pages with diagrams or graphs, specifically note whether the
diagram description is detailed enough to mark against (counts of
plotted points, approximate coordinates, drawn-line shape, etc.).

### 3. Per-page verdict (one sentence)

At the end of each transcript file, after the verbatim section
and the confidence note, add a single line:

`*Verdict:* easy | medium | hard`

…where "easy" means the handwriting was clear and the page was
trivial to read, "medium" means some interpretation was needed,
and "hard" means significant uncertainty that warrants a human
check.

